INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (67,1,'2026-07-01 11:25:40','2026-07-01 11:25:40','<p>Applications for the Summer 2027 WordPress research fellowship application are now open. Every year, the Northeastern University Department of Software Engineering invites a cohort of undergraduate students to join a ten-week paid research program. This year, we are expanding to six research tracks and welcoming a larger, more diverse group of fellows than ever before.</p>\n\n<h2>What the WordPress Research Fellowship Application 2027 Covers</h2>\n\n<p>The application asks for three things: a short statement of interest, a code sample or portfolio link, and a brief description of the problem in WordPress you most want to solve. You do not need prior WordPress experience. Strong PHP or JavaScript fundamentals are enough to get started. In fact, many of our most successful fellows arrived knowing only one of those languages.</p>\n\n<p>Furthermore, we look for curiosity and follow-through over specific tool experience. If you have shipped something small — a plugin, a theme, a CLI tool, a browser extension — that tells us more than a transcript. We want to see that you can take an idea from nothing to something working.</p>\n\n<h2>New Research Tracks for 2027</h2>\n\n<p>In addition to the existing tracks in plugin architecture, editor UX, performance, and accessibility, we are adding two new areas this year:</p>\n\n<ul>\n<li><strong>Developer Tooling</strong> — CLI tools, code generation, and local development workflows.</li>\n<li><strong>Cloud and Deployment</strong> — containerisation, multisite orchestration, and edge delivery for WordPress.</li>\n</ul>\n\n<p>Each track is led by a faculty mentor and supported by an industry partner from the WordPress ecosystem. Fellows meet weekly as a full cohort and also in smaller track teams. By the end of week ten, every track ships a working, publicly available deliverable.</p>\n\n<h2>Timeline and Stipend</h2>\n\n<p>The program runs from June 2 to August 8, 2027. Fellows receive a stipend of $6,000 for the ten weeks. Housing support is available for students relocating to Boston for the summer. The application deadline is December 1, 2026, and decisions go out by February 1, 2027.</p>\n\n<p>Therefore, if you are planning to apply for this WordPress research fellowship, we strongly recommend starting your statement of interest now rather than waiting until late November. The strongest applications we receive every year come from students who have clearly thought about the specific problem they want to work on.</p>\n\n<h2>How to Apply</h2>\n\n<p>Visit the <a href=\"/apply-eligibility/\">Apply and Eligibility page</a> for the full requirements and the application form. If you have questions, reach out to the program faculty through the <a href=\"/contact/\">Contact page</a>. We also hold two open question-and-answer sessions via Zoom in October and November — dates will be posted on this blog.</p>\n\n<p>We look forward to reading your applications. Good luck.</p>','Applications Open for Summer 2027 Fellows','Applications for the Summer 2027 cohort of the WordPress Research Fellows Program are now open. The program expands to six research tracks this year. Deadline: December 1, 2026.','publish','open','open','','applications-open-for-summer-2027-fellows','','','2026-07-03 18:38:09','2026-07-03 18:38:09','',0,'http://localhost:10005/applications-open-for-summer-2027-fellows/',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (68,1,'2026-06-24 11:25:41','2026-06-24 11:25:41','<p>WordPress block editor performance optimization was the central challenge for our performance track this summer. The block editor is powerful, but it carries significant front-end weight that can slow down the authoring experience — especially on lower-powered devices and slower connections. Our fellows set out to measure that weight precisely and to ship real improvements by the end of the program.</p>\n\n<h2>How We Measured Block Editor Performance</h2>\n\n<p>First, the team established a baseline. They created a representative test page with thirty blocks — a mix of paragraph, image, heading, list, and custom blocks — and profiled it with Chrome DevTools and WebPageTest. The key metric they tracked was time-to-interactive: the point at which the editor is fully usable after the page loads.</p>\n\n<p>The baseline came in at 4.2 seconds on a mid-range laptop over a throttled connection. That is a long time to wait before you can start writing. However, breaking down the waterfall revealed that two things dominated the load time: a large synchronously loaded script bundle and an inline block of global styles that the page did not actually use.</p>\n\n<h2>WordPress Block Editor Performance Optimization Techniques</h2>\n\n<p>The team made three targeted changes. First, they deferred non-critical block scripts so those scripts no longer block rendering. Second, they removed global styles output for blocks that were not registered on the test page. Third, they split the main editor bundle at a logical seam so the core editing surface loads before the toolbar and sidebar panels.</p>\n\n<p>In addition, they added a lightweight resource hint to preload the most commonly requested font. That single change shaved 300 milliseconds off the first contentful paint. These kinds of small, targeted interventions compound quickly when you apply several of them together.</p>\n\n<h2>Results and Upstream Contribution</h2>\n\n<p>After the three changes, time-to-interactive dropped from 4.2 seconds to 2.9 seconds — a 31% improvement. The team submitted their findings as a GitHub issue on the <a href=\"https://github.com/WordPress/gutenberg\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">Gutenberg repository</a> and two of the changes were accepted for the upcoming WordPress release.</p>\n\n<p>Therefore, this work will ship to millions of WordPress sites worldwide. That is exactly the kind of real-world impact the program aims for. See the rest of our <a href=\"/blog/\">project updates on the blog</a> for more examples of fellows contributing to open-source projects.</p>\n\n<p>Furthermore, this work gave every fellow on the track a new mental model for approaching performance: measure first, change one thing at a time, and verify the result before moving on. That discipline is more transferable than any specific technique.</p>','Building a Faster Block Editor: Performance Track Recap','Our performance track cut WordPress block editor time-to-interactive by nearly a third by deferring non-critical scripts and trimming global styles. A Summer 2026 recap.','publish','open','open','','building-a-faster-block-editor-performance-track-recap','','','2026-07-03 18:38:09','2026-07-03 18:38:09','',0,'http://localhost:10005/building-a-faster-block-editor-performance-track-recap/',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (69,1,'2026-06-17 11:25:42','2026-06-17 11:25:42','<p>Building accessible color systems that meet WCAG AA contrast requirements is harder than it looks. Most design systems specify a set of gray tones that look refined on a large monitor in a well-lit room. However, those same tones often fail contrast checks for users with low vision, or on screens with lower brightness settings. Our research notes track explored what happens when you audit a real design system and have to fix it without losing the brand.</p>\n\n<h2>The Problem With Muted Text Colors</h2>\n\n<p>The most common failure we find in design systems is muted text. A typical pattern is to use a mid-gray — something like #808080 — for secondary or helper text. That color achieves a contrast ratio of roughly 3.9:1 against white. WCAG AA requires 4.5:1 for normal text. So a color that looks acceptable to designers with standard vision fails for a significant portion of users.</p>\n\n<p>Furthermore, the failure compounds. When you use that muted gray on a card background that is itself a light gray rather than white, the ratio drops further. A 3.9:1 ratio can become 3.2:1 almost invisibly. This is why accessible color systems must be tested in context, not in isolation.</p>\n\n<h2>Our Accessible Color Systems WCAG AA Audit Process</h2>\n\n<p>We developed a three-step process that any team can repeat. First, export every text color token and its intended background context. Second, run each pair through a contrast checker — we used the <a href=\"https://www.w3.org/WAI/WCAG21/Understanding/contrast-minimum.html\" rel=\"noopener noreferrer\">WCAG 2.1 minimum contrast guidance</a> as our reference. Third, for every failing pair, find the darkest version of that color that still reads as the same hue before resorting to a new token entirely.</p>\n\n<p>In our case, the muted gray moved from #808080 to #595959. That is a meaningful step darker, but it still reads as secondary text rather than primary text. The contrast ratio at #595959 against white is 7:1, which exceeds WCAG AA and meets WCAG AAA. The brand does not break; the text simply becomes readable.</p>\n\n<h2>What We Learned About Accessible Color Systems</h2>\n\n<p>The key insight is that WCAG AA is a floor, not a ceiling. In addition, testing colors in isolation is not enough — always test them in their actual context. A color that passes at 4.6:1 on white may fail at 3.8:1 on your card background. The fix is never to pick an arbitrary darker shade; it is to understand the actual backgrounds the color will appear against and set the token accordingly.</p>\n\n<p>We also learned that accessible color decisions are easier to make early and much harder to retrofit. Therefore, we now include a contrast check as a required step in the design review process for every new component the program builds.</p>\n\n<p>Read more about our research on the <a href=\"/blog/\">research blog</a>, or learn about the program on the <a href=\"/about-the-program/\">About page</a>.</p>','Notes on Accessible Color Systems','How we audited a design system for WCAG AA accessible color contrast failures and fixed them without breaking the brand palette. A practical research note.','publish','open','open','','notes-on-accessible-color-systems','','','2026-07-03 18:38:09','2026-07-03 18:38:09','',0,'http://localhost:10005/notes-on-accessible-color-systems/',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (70,1,'2026-06-10 11:25:42','2026-06-10 11:25:42','<p>The WordPress research fellows 2026 cohort was the largest and most technically diverse group we have welcomed to date. Fourteen undergraduate students from the Northeastern University Department of Software Engineering joined four research tracks over ten weeks. Together they shipped work that is now part of the program infrastructure and, in two cases, contributed upstream to the WordPress project itself.</p>\n\n<h2>Who the 2026 WordPress Research Fellows Were</h2>\n\n<p>The cohort spanned all four class years, from freshmen to seniors. Most had completed at least two semesters of coursework in algorithms and object-oriented programming. However, prior WordPress experience was not required, and roughly half the group had never written a WordPress plugin before orientation week.</p>\n\n<p>Furthermore, the cohort was split evenly between students who preferred working in JavaScript and those who leaned toward PHP. That balance turned out to be an asset: the plugin architecture and editor UX tracks were able to collaborate closely because neither team was working in unfamiliar territory.</p>\n\n<h2>What the 2026 Cohort Built</h2>\n\n<p>The plugin architecture track shipped a reporting plugin that generates weekly summaries of application form submissions and emails them to faculty reviewers. That plugin is now running on this site and replaces a manual spreadsheet process. The editor UX track contributed two block patterns to the WordPress pattern directory. The performance track reduced editor load time by 31 percent on a representative test page. The accessibility track produced a checklist and audit tool now referenced in the program handbook.</p>\n\n<p>In addition, three fellows from the 2026 cohort have gone on to contribute to open-source WordPress projects independently after the program ended. That kind of continued engagement is one of the clearest signals that the program is working as intended.</p>\n\n<h2>Looking Ahead</h2>\n\n<p>Applications for the Summer 2027 cohort are now open. We are expanding to six research tracks and expecting our largest WordPress research fellows cohort yet. Therefore, if you are an undergraduate Software Engineering student at Northeastern, now is the time to apply.</p>\n\n<p>Visit the <a href=\"/apply-eligibility/\">Apply and Eligibility page</a> to learn more, or read the <a href=\"/about-the-program/\">About the Program page</a> for the full program overview. We look forward to welcoming the next group of fellows.</p>','Meet the 2026 Fellows','Meet the fourteen undergraduates who made up the 2026 WordPress Research Fellows cohort at Northeastern University and discover what they built over the summer.','publish','open','open','','meet-the-2026-fellows','','','2026-07-03 18:38:09','2026-07-03 18:38:09','',0,'http://localhost:10005/meet-the-2026-fellows/',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (71,1,'2026-06-03 11:25:43','2026-06-03 11:25:43','<p>WordPress plugin architecture extensibility was the guiding principle for our plugin architecture track this summer. The challenge was to build a reporting plugin for the fellows application form — a genuinely useful internal tool — while also making it a case study in how to write WordPress plugins that other developers can extend without forking the code.</p>\n\n<h2>The Core Design Problem in WordPress Plugin Architecture</h2>\n\n<p>Most internal tools start as single-purpose scripts and grow into hard-to-maintain code because they were never designed to be extended. However, if you design for extensibility from the start, you inevitably over-engineer something that did not need to be complex. Our track wanted to find the middle path: a plugin that is extensible enough to adapt to new requirements, but not so abstracted that it becomes hard to read.</p>\n\n<p>Therefore, the team adopted three principles early in the project. First, favor composition over configuration: build small, single-responsibility components that can be wired together rather than a large settings object that controls behaviour via flags. Second, keep the public API small — every hook you expose is a contract you must maintain. Third, document every hook at the point of definition, not in a separate wiki page that goes stale.</p>\n\n<h2>Applying WordPress Plugin Architecture Extensibility Patterns</h2>\n\n<p>One of the more interesting discoveries was the Abilities API, a modern alternative to capability checks that the team had not encountered in coursework. In addition to checking whether a user has a named capability, the Abilities API lets you describe what an action is — reading a record, editing a record, deleting a record — and then register rules that determine which roles can perform each action.</p>\n\n<p>This made the plugin significantly easier to test. Instead of mocking built-in capability functions throughout the codebase, the team could swap in a test implementation of the rules layer. That one architectural decision cut test setup time by roughly half.</p>\n\n<h2>What Shipped</h2>\n\n<p>The finished plugin generates weekly digest emails, exports application data as CSV, and exposes three documented action hooks for teams that want to add their own reporting outputs. Furthermore, the plugin is structured so that swapping out the email provider or the storage backend requires changing one class, not scattered function calls throughout the codebase.</p>\n\n<p>The plugin is now running in production on this site. For more on the technical details, see the <a href=\"/highlights-team/\">Highlights and Team page</a> or explore the rest of our <a href=\"/blog/\">research blog</a>.</p>','Plugin Architecture Track: Lessons in Extensibility','The plugin architecture track built an extensible WordPress reporting plugin using hooks, filters, and the Abilities API. Lessons in WordPress plugin architecture extensibility.','publish','open','open','','plugin-architecture-track-lessons-in-extensibility','','','2026-07-03 18:38:09','2026-07-03 18:38:09','',0,'http://localhost:10005/plugin-architecture-track-lessons-in-extensibility/',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (72,1,'2026-05-20 11:25:44','2026-05-20 11:25:44','<p>The research mentorship model at the heart of the WordPress Research Fellows Program is one of the things we think most carefully about each year. A ten-week program is short. Fellows arrive with varying backgrounds, and the research problems are genuinely open-ended. Without a clear mentorship structure, projects drift in the first three weeks and teams spend the last two weeks scrambling to ship something coherent.</p>\n\n<h2>How We Approach Faculty Student Pairing</h2>\n\n<p>The faculty student pairing process starts before orientation week. Fellows rank their top two track preferences in their application, and faculty mentors review the applications for the tracks they lead. We aim for a two-way match: the fellow should be excited about the problem, and the mentor should believe the fellow has the foundation to contribute meaningfully.</p>\n\n<p>Furthermore, we try to pair each fellow with a mentor whose research intersects — but does not exactly overlap — with the track topic. A mentor who already has all the answers tends to turn the fellowship into a directed-study course rather than a genuine research experience. The best mentors are curious alongside their fellows, not just ahead of them.</p>\n\n<h2>The Weekly Check-In Structure in Our Research Mentorship Model</h2>\n\n<p>Each fellow meets with their faculty mentor for thirty minutes once a week. The agenda follows a consistent format: what did you ship last week, what is blocking you this week, and what is your goal for the next seven days. The thirty-minute limit is intentional. It forces both parties to prepare, and it leaves the fellow responsible for the decisions that happen between meetings.</p>\n\n<p>In addition to the one-on-one, each track meets as a group for an hour every Thursday. That session is peer-led: fellows take turns presenting a problem they are working through and the group offers suggestions. Mentors attend but do not lead the discussion. This structure prevents the mentor from becoming the default answer-giver for every question.</p>\n\n<h2>What We Have Learned After Three Cohorts</h2>\n\n<p>After three cohorts, the pattern that predicts project success most reliably is not the fellow\'s prior experience. Instead, it is whether the fellow asks specific questions rather than vague ones in the first two weeks. Specific questions signal that they have engaged with the problem. Therefore, we now include a structured question-writing exercise in orientation week to build that habit early.</p>\n\n<p>The research mentorship model continues to evolve. We welcome feedback from alumni and current fellows — reach out through the <a href=\"/contact/\">Contact page</a> or read more about how the program is structured on the <a href=\"/about-the-program/\">About page</a>.</p>','Mentorship Model: How We Pair Fellows and Faculty','How the WordPress Research Fellows Program pairs undergraduates with faculty mentors, and the weekly check-in structure that keeps ten-week projects on track.','publish','open','open','','mentorship-model-how-we-pair-fellows-and-faculty','','','2026-07-03 18:38:09','2026-07-03 18:38:09','',0,'http://localhost:10005/mentorship-model-how-we-pair-fellows-and-faculty/',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (73,1,'2026-05-04 11:25:45','2026-05-04 11:25:45','<p>Welcome to the WordPress Research Fellows Program blog. This is the official publication channel for the program — run by the Department of Software Engineering at Northeastern University. Here you will find cohort announcements, project write-ups from fellows, and research notes from each track. If you are curious about what we are building and why, this is the right place to follow along.</p>\n\n<h2>What the WordPress Research Fellows Program Blog Will Cover</h2>\n\n<p>This blog will publish three types of content. First, announcements: application openings, deadlines, event dates, and program news. Second, project write-ups: post-mortems and recaps from each research track, written by the fellows themselves. Third, research notes: shorter, more technical posts about specific problems the tracks encounter — tools they find useful, patterns they discover, and decisions they make along the way.</p>\n\n<p>Furthermore, we will occasionally publish posts from program alumni who are continuing their WordPress work after the fellowship ends. We want this blog to be a record of the research community the program is building, not just a news feed.</p>\n\n<h2>How to Follow the WordPress Research Fellows Program Blog</h2>\n\n<p>You can subscribe to the blog via the RSS feed at <code>/feed/</code>. Posts are also announced on the program social channels. In addition, each post is tagged by category — Announcements, Project Updates, and Research Notes — so you can filter to the content most relevant to you.</p>\n\n<p>The category filter bar at the top of the <a href=\"/blog/\">blog listing</a> links directly to each category archive. If you only want to read the technical research notes, click that filter and you will see only those posts. If you want the broad view, the All filter shows the full feed in reverse chronological order.</p>\n\n<h2>A Note on the Research</h2>\n\n<p>Everything published on this WordPress Research Fellows Program blog is the real work of real students and faculty. We do not ghost-write or clean up the technical details for a general audience. Therefore, some posts will be more technical than others. That is intentional. The program exists to produce genuine contributions to the WordPress project and to the broader open-source ecosystem, and this blog exists to document that work honestly.</p>\n\n<p>Thank you for reading. We hope you find it useful. Start with the <a href=\"/about-the-program/\">About the Program page</a> if you are new here, or jump straight into the latest posts.</p>','Welcome to the Research Fellows Blog','Welcome to the official blog of the Northeastern University WordPress Research Fellows Program — your source for announcements, project updates, and research notes.','publish','open','open','','welcome-to-the-research-fellows-blog','','','2026-07-03 18:38:09','2026-07-03 18:38:09','',0,'http://localhost:10005/welcome-to-the-research-fellows-blog/',0,'post','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (96,0,'2026-07-03 20:59:26','2026-07-03 20:59:26','<!-- wp:nu/hero {\"eyebrow\":\"Summer Research Program\",\"heading\":\"WordPress Research Fellows\",\"lead\":\"A 10-week paid summer fellowship where undergraduate Software Engineering students build, test, and ship real WordPress tooling alongside faculty mentors.\",\"ctaLabel\":\"Apply Now\",\"ctaSlug\":\"apply-eligibility\",\"image\":\"hero.jpg\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:nu/stats {\"label\":\"Program at a glance\",\"stats\":[\"10|Weeks, paid\",\"4|Research tracks\",\"1:4|Mentor ratio\",\"24|Fellows / summer\"]} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:nu/section-header {\"eyebrow\":\"Program Overview\",\"heading\":\"Build the tools you use every day\",\"intro\":\"The WordPress Research Fellows Program pairs Software Engineering undergraduates with faculty mentors to solve real problems in plugin architecture, editor UX, performance, security, and accessibility — the same systems that power the department’s own web infrastructure.\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:nu/media-card {\"image\":\"mentor.jpg\",\"imageAlt\":\"Fellow working at a laptop with a mentor\",\"heading\":\"Hands-on, mentored research\",\"body\":\"Each fellow is paired with a faculty mentor and joins a small track team focused on one problem area — plugin architecture, editor UX, performance, or accessibility. No prior WordPress experience required, just solid PHP or JS fundamentals.\",\"reverse\":false,\"section\":\"section section-tight\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:nu/track-badges {\"label\":\"Research tracks\",\"tracks\":[\"Plugin Architecture\",\"Editor & Block UX\",\"Performance & Security\",\"Accessibility\",\"Developer Tooling\",\"Cloud & Deployment\"]} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:nu/media-card {\"image\":\"fellows.jpg\",\"imageAlt\":\"Fellows presenting a project\",\"heading\":\"Ship something real\",\"body\":\"Fellows don’t just study code — every track ships a working plugin, block, or theme feature to a real test site by week 10, presented at the end-of-summer showcase.\",\"reverse\":true,\"section\":\"section section-muted\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:nu/cta-band {\"heading\":\"Ready to spend your summer building?\",\"lead\":\"Applications for Summer 2027 open December 1, 2026.\",\"ctaLabel\":\"See Eligibility & Deadlines\",\"ctaSlug\":\"apply-eligibility\"} /-->\n','Home','A 10-week paid summer fellowship where undergraduate Software Engineering students build, test, and ship real WordPress tooling alongside faculty mentors.','inherit','closed','closed','','12-revision-v1','','','2026-07-03 20:59:26','2026-07-03 20:59:26','',12,'http://localhost:10005/?p=96',0,'revision','',0);
INSERT INTO `wp_posts` VALUES (97,0,'2026-07-03 21:11:23','2026-07-03 21:11:23','<!-- wp:nu/hero-billboard {\"eyebrow\":\"WordPress Research Fellows\",\"heading\":\"Build. Test. Ship.\",\"image\":\"hero.jpg\"} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:nu/pillars {\"heading\":\"A deep commitment to your research success\",\"intro\":\"Discover the value of a summer spent doing real WordPress research, and the mentorship, funding, and support behind every fellow along the way.\",\"items\":[\"network|Gain real-world experience|On a transformative research fellowship, you work full time in a small track team, shipping real WordPress tooling the department relies on every day.\",\"medal|Earn a paid fellowship|Every fellow receives a competitive 10-week stipend, and the program office connects you with scholarships, travel grants, and publication support.\",\"pyramid|Advance your career trajectory|Research and mentorship help you expand your knowledge, get published, and stand out to employers and graduate programs alike.\"]} /-->\n\n<!-- wp:nu/journey-cards {\"label\":\"Your research journey\",\"cards\":[\"collab.jpg|Fellows collaborating in a lab|Explore research opportunities|Search across our tracks — plugin architecture, editor UX, performance, security, and accessibility — and find the problem you want to own.|Explore the program|about-the-program\",\"mentor2.jpg|A fellow and mentor reviewing work together|Find a faculty mentor|Our faculty are leaders in their fields, and their guidance plays an enormous role in your research. See who you could be working with.|Meet the team|highlights-team\",\"fellows.jpg|Fellows presenting a project|Discover funding and deadlines|A paid 10-week stipend, plus awards that provide experiences, resources, and funding. Get info on eligibility, deadlines, and more.|Apply now|apply-eligibility\"]} /-->\n','Home','A 10-week paid summer fellowship where undergraduate Software Engineering students build, test, and ship real WordPress tooling alongside faculty mentors.','inherit','closed','closed','','12-revision-v1','','','2026-07-03 21:11:23','2026-07-03 21:11:23','',12,'http://localhost:10005/?p=97',0,'revision','',0);
